<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,756,1380,2077]" lastBlockId="8.[831,1437,258,632]" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">
Even at the species-level, we found no support for a monophyly of all the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Germar" authorityYear="1817" box="[394,474,1413,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Hypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[394,474,1413,1436]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">Hypera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species investigated here based on our COI data (
<figureCitation box="[422,489,1444,1468]" captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,186,1908,1929]" captionTargetBox="[155,1408,263,1896]" captionTargetId="graphics@3.[544,992,642,2095]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Best Maximum Likelihood tree as selected by MEGA) based on COI sequences of 142 samples of Curculionoidea (Chrysomelidae obtained by using MEGA 6. Values (over 50 %) of bootstrap support from 100 nodes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1040870/files/figure.svg" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, Supp. 1). In particular, the recorded genetic distances (
<tableCitation box="[494,577,1476,1501]" captionStart="Tables 1 - 8" captionStartId="11.[151,213,258,279]" captionText="Tables 1 - 8: COI Kimura 2 - Parameter genetic distances for a set of selected samples used in the present study. See the main text for further details." pageId="8" pageNumber="23">Table 3</tableCitation>
) were relatively low (from 0.003 to 0.012) for any of the three species of the 
<emphasis box="[238,401,1541,1564]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">H. nigrirostris</emphasis>
group [
<emphasis box="[504,625,1541,1564]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">nigrirostris</emphasis>
(Fabricius, 1775), 
<emphasis box="[237,329,1572,1595]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">ononidis</emphasis>
(Chevrolat, 1863) and 
<emphasis box="[620,756,1572,1595]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">melarynchus</emphasis>
(Olivier, 1807)]. The morphologically weakly supported hypothesis of the species status for 
<emphasis box="[570,756,1636,1661]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Germar" authorityYear="1817" box="[570,650,1638,1661]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Hypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypera</taxonomicName>
ononidis
</emphasis>
was already questioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stuben P. E. &amp; Schutte A &amp; Astrin J. J." box="[478,719,1668,1693]" journalOrPublisher="Towards an Integrative Taxonomy. Snudebiller" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 294" part="16" refString="Stuben P. E., Schutte A., Bayer Ch., Astrin J. J. 2015. The Molecular Weevil Identification Project (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea), Part II. Towards an Integrative Taxonomy. Snudebiller 16 (237): 1 - 294." title="The Molecular Weevil Identification Project (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea), Part II" type="journal article" year="2015">
Stüben 
<emphasis box="[569,625,1668,1693]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. (2015)
</bibRefCitation>
in their barcode approach. Although, obvious ecological differences are evident (
<emphasis box="[408,533,1733,1757]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">H. ononidis</emphasis>
lives on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[629,706,1734,1757]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Ononis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[629,706,1734,1757]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">Ononis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. and occurs in a sub-area of 
<emphasis box="[441,594,1766,1789]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">H. nigrirostris</emphasis>
, which accepts a wider range of 
<taxonomicName box="[352,456,1797,1820]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
). Therefore, a more recent speciation process (not yet detectable with the possibly too conservative COI-marker), and thus the evolution of eco-species at an early stage of differentiation might be an explanation for this circumstance. Interestingly also the morphologically close 
<emphasis box="[431,599,1957,1982]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">H. melarynchus</emphasis>
– living on the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,250,1989,2012]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[259,479,1990,2014]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[259,336,1990,2013]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Ononis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Ononis</taxonomicName>
ramosissima
</emphasis>
– clustered together with 
<emphasis box="[151,282,2021,2046]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">H. ononidis</emphasis>
+ 
<emphasis box="[324,445,2023,2046]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">nigrirostris</emphasis>
. However, 
<emphasis box="[581,756,2021,2046]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">H. melarynchus</emphasis>
shows several morphological characters (biggest species of all three&gt; 5 mm; rostrum long and slender, at least as long as pronotum; 7th article about as wide as club; elongate elytra parallel along middle; penis S-shaped in lateral view, tip elongate, tongue-like) that allow an unambiguous separation from 
<emphasis box="[1221,1383,386,409]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">H. nigrirostris</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[831,959,417,441]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">H. ononidis</emphasis>
, and therefore the species status has never been questioned. This provides further evidence that the 
<emphasis box="[874,995,482,505]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">nigrirostris</emphasis>
-species group might indeed represent a younger group where speciation is at an early stage with an incomplete lineage sorting and highlighting therefore the limited resolution power of the used barcoding marker (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Germann C." box="[881,1107,608,632]" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" pagination="41 - 118" part="83" refString="Germann C. 2010 a. Die Russelkafer der Schweiz - Checkliste (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea) mit Verbreitungsangaben nach biogeografischen Regionen. Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 83: 41 - 118." title="Die Russelkafer der Schweiz - Checkliste (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea) mit Verbreitungsangaben nach biogeografischen Regionen" type="journal article" year="2010">
Germann 
<emphasis box="[987,1034,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
., 2010
</bibRefCitation>
for 
<bibRefCitation author="Germann C." box="[1151,1163,609,632]" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" pagination="41 - 118" part="83" refString="Germann C. 2010 a. Die Russelkafer der Schweiz - Checkliste (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea) mit Verbreitungsangaben nach biogeografischen Regionen. Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 83: 41 - 118." title="Die Russelkafer der Schweiz - Checkliste (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea) mit Verbreitungsangaben nach biogeografischen Regionen" type="journal article" year="2010" yearSuffix="a">a</bibRefCitation>
similar case in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" authorityYear="1758" box="[1331,1416,608,631]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
